<b>Prelude: </b> <br />
<br />
In the southern part of Freeport is an old tavern that has stood against the test of time, not to mention more than a thousand bar fights. Fredrick MacFerris is the current owner of this tavern, and before him, his father was, and before him, his father was, and before him… well. You get the picture. It has been a family establishment for quite some time. The outside of the tavern is the same worn, wooden building like all the others around it. There is no name on the sign above the door, just a big, roughly painted goat’s head. Even without a sign indicating that this was a tavern, and not a meat vendor or such, business was good for Fredrick. The regular patrons were enough to keep him going, as well as keeping the local militia paid for looking the other way at some of the more inhuman races, such as Trolls, Ogres, and even Iksars that frequented his establishment. <br />
<br />
Now, the regular patrons were not so much people that lived here in this section of town, but adventurers passing through town. By word of mouth, knowledge of his bar was passed among adventurers. Here whether they be human, elf, dwarf, erudite, troll, or whatever race, all were welcome, as long as they had the money to pay for their drinks and food. Also, his tavern was a favorite gathering place where adventurers would come here to try to recruit other adventurers to group with for treasures and, of course, more adventure. There was even a message board that Fredrick himself built so that the patrons could leave postings of quests that someone may need help with. This made it easier to get together. For these reasons, his tavern was kept pretty busy. <br />
<br />
Now, Fredrick kept to himself for the most part. He knew from experience not to stick his nose in to where it didn’t belong. He did, however, write down in a journal of his, some of the stories that he heard from the various drunk adventure who just had to share his latest quest. Every now and then, he would read a story from that journal to the crowd right before closing. Over time, his journal became the tavern’s public journal, and many an adventurer would ask to have his quest or journey entered into the growing list of stories. It was soon considered an honor to be included in the journal that had become known as ‘The Goathead’s Tavern Tales’. <br />
<br />
<br />
<u><b>Aeleric, the Wandering Minstrel</b></u><br />
<br />
<br />
<u><b>Chapter 1: Adventures, Ale, and Anna</b></u> <br />
<br />
The setting sun cast an orange tint across the old wood of the entrance. Aeleric opened the door and was immediately immersed in the noise of conversation and laughter, smell of delicious food and ale. He wandered over to a corner table that allowed him the view of the entire room, kitchen area entrance, and the tavern’s front entrance. He was not being chased, but did this out of habit. Aeleric always liked to sit where he could see everything that was going on. This way, he could judge the situations around him and decide upon out what songs and tales could be played to enhance the moods of the crowds. He was a jovial wood elf, and loved to play his many songs to whomever would like to listen. <br />
<br />
Tonight found him here in the GoatHead’s Tavern. He had heard of this place from a group of travelers in Planes of Knowledge, and so decided to check out the place for himself. He was always up for questing and seeing new lands. <br />
<br />
Aeleric signaled for one of the GoatHead’s barmaids. A very cute dark elf came over to where he sat. <br />
<br />
“What can I get for you t’day, sir” asked the barmaid. <br />
<br />
“Bring me some freshly cooked meat, some cheese, and bread. Oh, and some of your local ale to wash it down with, if you would please.” Aeleric said. <br />
<br />
The barmaid hurried off and returned with a mug of ale, and leaned over while setting it down, giving Aeleric a nice view of her dark blue, firm bosom. <br />
<br />
“What’s a beautiful girl like you serving to people? They should be serving to you.” asked Aeleric with a twinkling in his eyes. The barmaid smiled and softly giggled. <br />
<br />
“Your eyesight has gone on you, sir. I’m a bit old to be a girl, but the flattery is much appreciated” replied the barmaid. “My name is Anna, by the way. Your food will be ready in a bit.” <br />
<br />
“Well Anna,” said Aeleric. “The view is very much appreciated, and my name is Aeleric. I will await your return as another chance to win you over”, he said with a winking of his eye. <br />
<br />
She tried to seem put off with him, but he saw a smile on her lips as she walked away. He enjoyed putting a smile on people’s faces. He especially enjoyed it when that smile was on the face of such a gorgeous creature as Anna. <br />
<br />
With the image of Anna’s swaying hips walking away, he returned to scanning the room. The tavern had a firepit in the far corner, and lanterns here and there, but not enough to completely lighten the interior of the room. The outer tables, his included, that were the farthest from the fire were somewhat overcast in shadow. The doorway he had come through into the tavern was bathed in average lamplight, as well as the main bar. There were several people here, as well as different races. It seemed what that group up in Planes of Knowledge said was true. No one here seemed to harbor misgivings about different races within these walls. Here and there he saw different races in mixed conversations. Trolls chatting with humans, an iksar laughing at something a dwarf had just said. A Halfling was telling what seemed to be a tall tale of how he had saved some kid from a cyclops attack in West Commons when Anna came back with his food. She placed it in front of him, again allowing a good view of what her top-loosened bodice concealed. <br />
<br />
“Thank you kindly for this food” said Aeleric. “It will help me to have energy for later tonight”. <br />
<br />
“Oh?! And why would you need energy for later tonight”, asked Anna. <br />
<br />
“Why, so that I can win you, as well as this crowd, over with my musical talents. That is if it allowed here that bards may play”, replied Aeleric. <br />
<br />
She gave Aeleric an appraising eye. “If you would like, I will mention it to Fredrick. He is the owner of this tavern. I am sure that he would not mind.” <br />
<br />
“That would be great”, said Aeleric. “I am sure that I have some songs that would please even this mixed of a crowd”. <br />
<br />
“Maybe you may even have a song or two that would please me as well”, Anna said with a wink, and strode off toward the barkeep. <br />
<br />
He could swear that as she walked off, Anna had put an extra sway in in her hips, just for him! Sometimes he really relished being very charismatic. And these were one of those days. <br />
<br />
He ate the juicy, perfectly seasoned meat, cheese and warmed bread, all the while listening to the different stories and rumors being told. As he was washing down some of the bread with his ale, the barkeep came over and sat down across from him. <br />
<br />
“Hello there, Aeleric is it? Name’s Frederick. Frederick MacFerris. Friends call me Goat. Long story. It ties in with the name of the bar.” <br />
<br />
“Any way, Anna says that you are a bard and wish to play some songs and tell some tales for my customers. I think that can be arranged. We often have bards come through and play for the crowds. I’ll tell you what. If they are kept happy and content, then your ale and food will be at my expense.” <br />
<br />
“Hello there, Frederick”, replied Aeleric. “What Anna tells you is true. I would very much like to play and sing some tales that I have gathered throughout my travels. I assure you that I have rarely had any complaints about my singing and storytelling.” <br />
<br />
“Well, sounds good to me, Aeleric. Go ahead and finish your food and drink. When you are ready, just grab your instrument and head over to that small platform to the right.” <br />
<br />
Aeleric glanced over and saw the raised wooden platform, and noticed that Anna was lighting the overhead lamp which started to cast a soft light over the platform. <br />
<br />
“Best get back behind the bar. Thirsty customers and all.” And with that, Frederick left Aeleric’s table and headed back behind the bar to serve out more drinks. <br />
<br />
Aeleric finished his food, wiped his hands on a cloth, and pulled out his Combine Mandolin from its case. He had bought the mandolin in Katta Castellum, during one of his many adventures. As he checked its tuning, he realized that the surrounding chatter and noise in the tavern had slowly subsided. He looked up and noticed that most, if not all the tavern’s inhabitants were looking his way. ‘Here goes nothing’, he thought to himself, as he got up with mandolin in hand and headed over to the platform and sat down on a provided barstool that was placed there. <br />
<br />
Without pause, he started into a well-known song about a battle between a wurm and Halflings. This got a cheer from the Halflings in the crowded room, as well as applause from the rest of the crowd. Aeleric then preceded to sing songs of other quests, adventures, and women, and life. As he sang, he wove his magic into his songs, putting all at ease and allowing everyone listening to “see” all that Aeleric sang about in their mind’s eye. After about 15 different songs, he needed a break and some ale. <br />
<br />
“Thank you for your kind applause and cheers. Let me quench my dry throat and I will give you some more merriment in a bit.”</div>
