		<div>Aeleric walked back to his table, and as he sat down, Anna came over and put an ale in front of him. <br />
<br />
“This one is on the Iksar over near the bar in the blue armor. I guess he thinks that you are pretty good,” she said. <br />
“And what do you think, Anna?” asked Aeleric. <br />
Flashing a smile that could melt the Western Wastes, Anna said, “I think that you have yet to prove yourself to me yet, Minstrel”. And with that, she sauntered back toward the bar. <br />
<br />
Aeleric smiled to himself. She sure is a playful one, that Anna. <br />
<br />
Aeleric picked up the mug, and with a raised salute of the mug toward the Iksar that had bought it for him, took a long swig of the deliciously cold ale. <br />
<br />
The Iksar got up, headed toward Aeleric and sat down. <br />
<br />
“Well played, minstrel. My name is Shamscale, and I wanted to let you know that I and my group enjoyed your talents.” He indicated to the table he had just left, which had an Human, a lovely Wood Elf, and a lovely High Elf sitting at it. <br />
<br />
“Interesting companions, if I may say so, Shamscale. My name is Aeleric Battlesinger. I am glad that you liked my songs. I hope you did not mind my tale about how the Halfling outsmarted the Iksar that wanted to eat him.” <br />
<br />
“Not in the least, Aeleric. My friends poke fun at me all the time, and after all it is just a song.” <br />
“The beautiful Wood Elf that I was sitting beside is Mommadela, a druid and my wife. My human friend there is Marriedman, a very competent Mage, and beside him is the lovely Willowee, an enchanter and his wife. Our guild is known as Call of the Phoenix, and we would very much like you to join us on a questing of ours. With your song magic, it would be an added ability to our group.” <br />
<br />
Aeleric looked to Shamscale, and then to his group over at the other table. “What questing have your been tasked with, Shamscale?” <br />
<br />
Shamscale took a sip of swig of his ale. “We have been talking with one of the Lesser God’s Questgivers that have shown up recently, and have been tasked with collecting various things from the Kunarkian continent. If you would like, we could have you talk with the same Questgiver, and we could all go on this adventure throughout the different lands of Kunark. The reward is that of an elixir of Scholarship, used to help an individual gain in his levels of study at an incredible rate! I’ll tell you what. I will leave you alone, and if you choose to travel along with us, meet us in five days near the Druid ring in West Commons close to sunrise. Oh. You can bring a friend if you like. We will not mind at all.” <br />
<br />
Aeleric looked quizzically at Shamscale. “A friend? I’m not sure that I know anyone here right now, but I will consider your gracious offer.” <br />
<br />
“Surely you notice that …” Shamscale started and then stopped smiling a curious smirk. <br />
<br />
“All is well, Aeleric. I hope to see you there.” And with that he rose up out of his chair. <br />
<br />
The crowd started getting loud again, calling for more of Aeleric’s songs. Shamscale headed back to his group while Aeleric got out of his chair and headed back to the platform and entertained the crowd until closing, while at the same time entertaining the thought of traveling to Kunark with Shamscale and his group. <br />
<br />
While the last few patrons were walking out the door, Aeleric walked up to the bar where Frederick was cleaning the last of the mugs. <br />
<br />
“Frederick, I was wondering if you could suggest a good, honest place to stay around here. It seems that I will be staying in the area for a few days. “ <br />
I also would like to know if I could entertain the patrons while I’m here in town in exchange for some food and ale”, Aeleric said. <br />
<br />
Frederick stopped and thought a moment. “Well, as far as entertaining the patrons, you sure can! My tips haven’t been this good in quite some time! As far as places to stay, there are a couple of places that I could recommend. Just over the next…” <br />
<br />
Anna interrupted before Frederick could finish. “Don’t worry, Frederick. I will take care of where he can stay while here.” <br />
<br />
And without so much as a word, Anna grabbed the bewildered Bard’s arm and headed out the tavern’s door and into the night. <br />
<br />
Frederick chuckled to himself. He hoped Aeleric could sing a song of stamina, for he had an idea that Aeleric would soon be needing it.</div>
